":"Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Hesketh Bank, Lancashire, England":"Hesketh Bank, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hesketh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from Hesketh (Lancashire), Hesketh Grange in Felixkirk (North Yorkshire), or Hesket in the Forest (Cumberland). The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>hestr</i> ‘horse, stallion’ + <i>skeith</i> ‘course, track, race course’. The ancient Scandinavians were fond of horse-racing and horse-fighting, and introduced both pastimes to England."],"variants":[{"name":"Heskett","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Lancashire): variant of   Hesketh  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":39,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":48,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Hesketh was born in 1176, in Hesketh Bank, Lancashire, England, his father, William Hesketh, was 32 and his mother, Annabel de Stafford, was 22. He married Lady Elbora de Totleworth in 1198, in Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1230, in Rufford, Lancashire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1176–1230":"1176–1230","–Male":"Surnud","1178–1220":"1178–1220","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1154–Female":"1154–Surnud","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1145":"1145","1178":"1178","1176":"1176","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1154":"1154","1230":"1230","about 1166":"umbes 1166","Rufford Manor, Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","England":"England","